[17]
They submit that the decision was unreasonable because:
a. the Board failed to engage in a contextual approach to assessing state protection;
b. the documentary evidence before the Board supported the conclusion that effective state protection was not available to them;
c. the Board mentioned only documentary evidence from 2004-2006 and failed to consider more recent evidence;
d. the Board failed to explain why the relied upon evidence is preferred to contradictory evidence;
e. the Board failed to consider the response of the police in Veracruz, which they state is indicative of the response that the claimants would have received in Mexico City; and
f. the Board failed to consider evidence that the police in Mexico cannot protect themselves, let alone ordinary citizens.
